SKILL|github-auth|"GitHub auth setup: HTTPS tokens, SSH keys, gh CLI login."
STEP|1|**`git` (always available)** — uses HTTPS personal access tokens or SSH keys
STEP|2|**`gh` CLI (if installed)** — richer GitHub API access with a simpler auth flow
STEP|3|Decision tree:**
STEP|4|If `gh auth status` shows authenticated → you're good, use `gh` for everything
STEP|5|If `gh` is installed but not authenticated → use "gh auth" method below
STEP|6|If `gh` is not installed → use "git-only" method below (no sudo needed)
STEP|7|Step 1: Create a personal access token**
STEP|8|Click "Generate new token (classic)"
STEP|9|Give it a name like "hermes-agent"
STEP|10|Select scopes:
STEP|11|Set expiration (90 days is a good default)
STEP|12|Copy the token — it won't be shown again
STEP|13|Step 2: Configure git to store the token**
STEP|14|Alternative: cache helper (credentials expire from memory)**
STEP|15|Alternative: set the token directly in the remote URL (per-repo)**
STEP|16|Step 3: Configure git identity**
STEP|17|Step 4: Verify**
STEP|18|Step 1: Check for existing SSH keys**
STEP|19|Step 2: Generate a key if needed**
STEP|20|Click "New SSH key"
STEP|21|Paste the public key content
STEP|22|Give it a title like "hermes-agent-<machine-name>"
STEP|23|Step 3: Test the connection**
STEP|24|Step 4: Configure git to use SSH for GitHub**
STEP|25|Step 5: Configure git identity**
PIT|**`git` (always available)** — uses HTTPS personal access tokens or SSH keys
PIT|**`gh` CLI (if installed)** — richer GitHub API access with a simpler auth flow
PIT|Decision tree:**
PIT|If `gh auth status` shows authenticated → you're good, use `gh` for everything
PIT|If `gh` is installed but not authenticated → use "gh auth" method below
PIT|If `gh` is not installed → use "git-only" method below (no sudo needed)
PIT|Step 1: Create a personal access token**
PIT|Click "Generate new token (classic)"
PIT|Give it a name like "hermes-agent"
PIT|Select scopes:
PIT|Set expiration (90 days is a good default)
PIT|Copy the token — it won't be shown again
PIT|Step 2: Configure git to store the token**
PIT|Alternative: cache helper (credentials expire from memory)**
PIT|Alternative: set the token directly in the remote URL (per-repo)**
PIT|Step 3: Configure git identity**
PIT|Step 4: Verify**
PIT|Step 1: Check for existing SSH keys**
PIT|Step 2: Generate a key if needed**
